I'm taking a last-minute stab at a wireframe for some technical policies \
and principles for our group, as promised. Thorny, you might try to \
flesh things out a little, or the group might just want to talk about \
how these might be articulated, the extent to which they touch on other \
groups, or whether they could be just refactored into a list of \
assumptions we'll develop during our upcoming meeting. (I'll be away for \
the next call.)\
\
The original activities draft Jon wrote had some good questions that \
identify areas for policies/principles. Here's an extraction of those, \
with some proposed positions drawn from our conversations a little, with \
some personal bias to get the discussion going. :)\
\
* Platform requirements\
\
Because participation is to a large extent voluntary, the technical \
architecture should place as few restrictions on implementors as \
possible, but needs to state a strong preference for at least the \
following criteria of standardization:\
   - adherence to relevant standards, i.e., *proper* and *valid*\
     although not necessarily *fully complete* implementations are\
     highly preferred, especially where interoperability is concerned\
   - where code may be shared to other institutions, reasonable\
     consideration given to abstraction at appropriate levels; for\
     example, modularized database APIs to allow for portability,\
     avoidance of OS-specific technologies\
   - attention to scalability, i.e. proof-of-concept models should not\
     be supplied as surrogates for reliable production systems\
\
* Open source versus commercial tools\
\
The nature of our project (emerging standards) and the nature of our \
institutions (not-for-profit) lead us to prefer the track record of open \
source software, which have provided excellent reference implementations \
of developing technologies, a minimal threat of proprietary influence, \
data migration problems, etc. However, in the interest of encouraging \
participation and achieving interoperability, we place adherence to \
standards at a higher priority.\
\
Replication/redundancy/scalability/performance\
\
For initial work, the focus should be on functionality and not \
performance. However, all work should be done with an eye toward \
scalability. In particular:\
- OAI-based work in the first two phases should focus on standardization \
and common practices, so that replication will be easy to achieve, and \
will produce consistent results for users. This will enable multiple \
sites to be put on line that harvest the same material and provide \
roughly the same search experience.\
- Work in future stages that may involve distributed technology should \
focus on evolving standards for those technologies, as well as \
methodologies for increasing capacity to prevent performance problems as \
usage grows.\
- In general, as architectures introduce interdependencies, the standard \
principles of avoiding single points of failure should be followed.\
