Here is my addition (driven by early-morning coffee) to what Cory \
originally wrote. I think that there is some overlap but I wanted to add \
a dimension that was more about the abstract architecture. It also \
should be assumed that my list was not intended to be complete nor \
without my prejudices!\
\
thorny\
\
   * Architectural Requirements\
\
The main goal for this project is (apparently!) to build services that \
can be used broadly without requiring absolute agreement on how to \
implement a content management strategy locally.  The following \
assumptions would seem to be required:\
\
- Discovery services are very important. The purpose of these services \
is to actally find things. Users who find digital resources often want \
to do something with the resource found immediately, sometimes to gather \
them for later use.\
\
- The Aquifer definition of interoperablility will be based on the idea \
of exposing metadata for arbitrary use. That metadata will include that \
needed for discovery as well as metadata that characterizes the content \
found.\
\
- The architecture should support harvesting for use by members of the \
consortium and for arbitrary aggregators without any built-in prejudice.\
\
- Fine-grained policies about how the data can be used and by whom \
should be enforceable throughout the lifecycle of the exposed information.\
\
- The architecture should be sufficiently abstract to support a wide \
variety of implementations.\
